<subSubSection pageId="18" pageNumber="753" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="18.[112,649,1008,1509]" box="[113,213,1008,1034]" pageId="18" pageNumber="753">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="18.[112,649,1008,1509]" pageId="18" pageNumber="753">
All specimens agree in idiosoma sclerotization and setation of appendages with specimens from continental Europe (
<bibRefCitation author="GERECKE R." box="[337,494,1103,1129]" pageId="18" pageNumber="753" pagination="141 - 378" refId="ref20484" refString="GERECKE R. 2003. - The water mites of the genus Atractides Koch, 1837 (Acari: Parasitengona: Hygrobatidae) in the western Palaearctic region: a revision. Zoological Journal of the Linnean Society 138: 141 - 378." type="journal article" year="2003">Gerecke 2003</bibRefCitation>
), but differ in measurements and proportions of I-L-5/6 (both segments longer, L ratio I-L-5/6&gt; 4.3, setae S-1/-2 longer and more distanced, and P-3/-4 (more slender). Furthermore, the female genital plates are more elongate, with acetabula arranged in a weakly curved line while they are triangular in central European specimens. Before weighting the genetical significance of these differences, more information is necessary on variability in the still understudied central European populations. In the following, I give a survey of measurements of the Sardinian specimens.
</paragraph>
